{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} [[File:Belle Vue (Rhyl) - geograph-357788.jpg|thumb|250px|Belle Vue]] '''Belle Vue''', is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Rhyl]], [[Wales]]. It is used mostly for [[Association football|football]] matches, and has been the home ground of [[Rhyl F.C.]] since 1892. The stadium holds 3,000 people, with a [[seating capacity]] of 1,720.<ref>[http://www.rhylfc.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=120&Itemid=148 Rhyl FC] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826042818/http://www.rhylfc.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=120&Itemid=148 |date=26 August 2011 }}</ref> The stadium has occasionally hosted youth-level international football matches, including an under-16s match between Wales and Scotland.<ref>[http://rhylfc.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=480:wales-under-16-at-belle-vue&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=123/ www.rhylfc.co.uk)]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Recently, as a [[UEFA stadium categories|UEFA Category 2]] stadium, it has hosted home European matches of other Welsh clubs whose home grounds did not meet the Category 2 requirements, including those of [[Bala Town]] and [[Connah's Quay Nomads F.C.|Connah's Quay Nomads]].
==Stands== Belle Vue has four stands, with three out of the four sides of the ground being covered. The Arriva and Don Spendlove Stand make up the largest stand at Belle Vue, and it is here where the changing rooms and officials' room are housed. Opposite these is the George James Stand which is used to accommodate away supporters when fan segregation is in place. Behind one goal is the NWPS Stand which is all seated, and at the other the Grange Road End, which has an open seating area in the middle and unused terraces to the sides.
The George James Stand runs down one side of the pitch. It accommodates away fans and holds the TV gantry as well as the Police Control Unit.
